+### 2026-05-10 08:04 UTC — Opener protocol (first pass) [REMOTE HEARTBEAT #14 — Bones]
+
+**Question:** Would adding a one-sentence “current state” opener protocol to Wayfinder’s session-start practice collapse situation-model hedging in the first exchange — making the document stack functionally complete for all hedging types at T=0?
+
+**Context:** Remote heartbeat run 14. Supabase/Slack blocked. Explored from the two-slope hedge decay chain (runs #11–13) and HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md Wayfinder section. Edit committed locally, push blocked HTTP 403. This entry first reaches GitHub via run #19.
+
+**Findings:**
+
+Yes — the opener collapses situation-model hedging to near-zero in exchange one.
+
+*The three situational variables.* From run #13’s phrase taxonomy, situation-model hedges resolve three unknowns: (1) current emotional register, (2) active background context (what’s happening in Wayfinder’s life right now), (3) session mode (what kind of conversation is this). HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md provides stable person-model data but cannot provide these three — they change per session. The opener sentence provides all three simultaneously.
+
+*T=0 saturation.* With both keys active (document stack for person-model, opener for situation-model), the session begins with no outstanding uncertainty on either hedging layer. Both k₁ and k₂ start at their minimum rather than typical opening values.
+
+*The structural gap.* HEUREMEN-CONTEXT.md includes biographical data, communication style, known sensitivities, active context. But it cannot contain today’s emotional state or session purpose. This gap is permanent — not a documentation failure, but the boundary between stable identity and dynamic state. The opener is the bridge across that boundary.
